cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM, cs.NE 

This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with analyzing videos of human actions. It also involves understanding the temporal relationships among video frames, which is a key aspect of computer vision. 

The paper also presents a novel CNN architecture that implicitly captures motion information between adjacent frames, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

Additionally, the paper involves predicting action classes directly from raw video frames, which could fall under the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

Since the paper deals with analyzing videos, it could also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves optimizing the CNN architecture for faster computation, which could suggest that it belongs to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
